               <p>BENJAMIN SOARES WILLIS. I am in the house of Smith, Payne, and Smith. I was on <placeName id="t18290611-352-crimeloc1847">Ludgate-hill</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290611-352-crimeloc1847" type="placeName" value="Ludgate-hill"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290611-352-crimeloc1847" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290611-352-off1845 t18290611-352-crimeloc1847"></join>, and lost my handkerchief from my coat pocket; I did not feel it, but was told of it - I had had it five minutes before; I turned round, and a friend pointed out the prisoner, who was about three yards from me, and had his hand in his right-side pocket - I ran up to him, pulled out his hand, and my handkerchief was in it.</p>

               <p>GEORGE HUSSEY. I was walking with Mr. Willis; I saw the prisoner close behind him - I watched, and saw him draw his hand from Mr. Willis' pocket and put it into his own - I asked Willis if he had lost a handkerchief - he said he had, and took it from the prisoner's hand.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290611-352-person2466">
                  RICHARD 
                  AMBROSE
               <interp inst="t18290611-352-person2466" type="surname" value="AMBROSE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-352-person2466" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-352-person2466" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I was standing by and took the prisoner; I found two other handkerchiefs on him, all of different patterns.</p>
               <p>The prisoner put in a written Defence, stating that his handkerchief was thrown at him, and as nobody owned it he put it into his pocket.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18290611-352-verdict1848" type="verdictDescription">
